 the Mexican American community, which continued to experience informal segregation long after federal and state laws officially ended the practice. In this historical ethnography, Jennifer R. Nájera offers a layered rendering and analysis of Mexican segregation in a South Texas community in the first half of the twentieth century. Using oral histories and local archives, she brings to life Mexican origin peoples’ experiences with segregation. Through their stories and supporting documentary evidence, Nájera shows how the ambiguous racial status of Mexican origin people allowed some of them to be exceptions to the rule of Anglo racial dominance. She demonstrates that while such exceptionality might suggest the permeability of the color line, in fact the selective and limited incorporation of Mexicans into Anglo society actually reinforced segregation by creating an illusion that the community had been integrated and no further changes were needed. Nájera also reveals how the actions of everyday people ultimately challenged racial/racist ideologies and created meaningful spaces for Mexicans in spheres historically dominated by Anglos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rightszTexaszLa FeriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxSegregationzTexaszLa FeriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericanszTexaszLa FeriavBiography. 0aOral historyzTexaszLa Feria. 0aRace discriminationzTexaszLa FeriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial movementszTexaszLa FeriaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767560423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767560/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_E